\begin{document}

Naohito,

Thank you very much for responding to my inquiries so far. I have been
working through your 1993 paper, Geometrical Structures of Some
Non-Distance Models for Asymmetric MDS. Here is something I am
wondering about. You define the seminorm (page 38)

\begin{equation}
  \label{eq:n1}
  \|\zeta\|=\sqrt{\phi(\zeta,\zeta)}
\end{equation}

and then say, ``in particular, if $\phi$ is positive for any
$\zeta\neq{}0,\|\zeta\|$ defines a \emph{norm}.'' Let me defend the
claim that $\sqrt{\phi(\zeta,\zeta)}$ \textbf{never} defines a norm
because the diagonal matrix $\Lambda$ is always indefinite (i.e.\ it
always contains at least one negative and one positive real number).
Let's call this claim ALWAYS-INDEF.

Recall that $\phi$ was defined as follows:

\begin{equation}
  \label{eq:n2}
  \phi(\zeta,\tau)=\zeta\Lambda\tau^{*}
\end{equation}

and 

\begin{equation}
  \label{eq:n3}
  \Lambda=\diag(\lambda_{1},\ldots,\lambda_{n})
\end{equation}

where the $\lambda_{j}$ are the eigenvalues of $H$ as defined on page
36. $H$ is a Hermitian matrix, and I will claim that for Hermitian
matrices

\begin{equation}
  \label{eq:n4}
  \sum_{j=1}^{n}\lambda_{j}=0.
\end{equation}

In other words, the trace of $\Lambda$ is $0$. ALWAYS-INDEF follows
immediately unless $\Lambda=0$, which is a trivial case. Consider

\begin{equation}
  \label{eq:n5}
  \det(H-\lambda{}I)=
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc}
        -\lambda & k_{12} & k_{13} \\
        k_{21} & -\lambda & k_{23} \\
        k_{31} & k_{32} & -\lambda 
      \end{array}
\right].
\end{equation}















